# Main useful functions

## Find a node by id

```js
function getNode(id) {
  for (let i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
    if (nodes[i].id === id) return nodes[i];
  }
  return null;
}
```

---

## Physics update for nodes

This is the main simulation.

### 1) Pairwise repulsion

Each pair of nodes repels each other using an inverse-square-like force:

```js
for each pair (i, j):
  dx = nodes[i].x - nodes[j].x
  dy = nodes[i].y - nodes[j].y
  dist = sqrt(dx*dx + dy*dy) || 1
  force = config.attraction / (dist * dist)

  fx = dx / dist * force
  fy = dy / dist * force

  nodes[i].vx += fx
  nodes[i].vy += fy
  nodes[j].vx -= fx
  nodes[j].vy -= fy
```

Despite the config key being named `attraction`, this part acts like **repulsion** because it pushes nodes apart along `dx, dy`.

---

### 2) Spring constraints on linked nodes

For each link:

```js
na = getNode(link.a)
nb = getNode(link.b)

dx = nb.x - na.x
dy = nb.y - na.y
dist = sqrt(dx*dx + dy*dy) || 1

stretch = dist - link.rest
force = (link.k || config.theta) * stretch

na.vx += dx / dist * force
na.vy += dy / dist * force
nb.vx -= dx / dist * force
nb.vy -= dy / dist * force
```

This makes linked nodes behave like springs with a preferred distance `rest`.

---

### 3) Centering + damping + integration

Each node is gently pulled toward the center `(400, 300)` and velocity is damped:

```js
for each node:
  node.vx += (400 - node.x) * config.dispersal
  node.vy += (300 - node.y) * config.dispersal

  node.vx *= config.amplification   // 0.92
  node.vy *= config.amplification

  node.x += node.vx
  node.y += node.vy
```

So:
- nodes don’t drift off forever
- friction reduces oscillation

